data.content:
`SafeAreaEdges="None"` tells the page not to add safe-area padding to its content, but you also need to ensure the app is actually **drawing behind the system bars**:

**Android** — You need to opt into edge-to-edge rendering. In your `MainActivity.cs` (or `MauiProgram.cs` platform lifecycle):

```csharp
// MainActivity.cs
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    // Enable drawing behind system bars
    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);

    // Make system bars transparent
    Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);
    Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);
}
```

> Note: .NET 10 targeting Android 15+ enforces edge-to-edge automatically, but you still need the transparent bar colors.

**iOS** — `SafeAreaEdges="None"` should suffice at the page level, but if the `Image` is inside a layout, also set `IgnoreSafeArea` on the view:

```xml
<ContentPage SafeAreaEdges="None">
    <Image Source="photo.jpg"
           Aspect="AspectFill"
           ios:Page.UseSafeArea="False" />
</ContentPage>
```

**Common gotcha** — Check that no parent `Grid`, `StackLayout`, or `Shell` is adding its own `Padding` or `Margin`. Shell's navigation chrome can also prevent true full-bleed; consider using `Shell.NavBarIsVisible="False"` on that page if appropriate.
